/DEV8049/SYSTEM/AWG/CHANNELGROUPING.Description: Sets the channel grouping mode of the device.

Options.0: Use the outputs in groups of 2. One sequencer program controls 2 outputs (use /dev..../awgs/0..4/).
Options.1: Use the outputs in groups of 4. One sequencer program controls 4 outputs (use /dev..../awgs/0/ and /dev..../awgs/2/)
Options.2: Use the outputs in groups of 8. One sequencer program controls 8 outputs (use /dev..../awgs/0/). Requires 8 channel device.

Options.0: Internal clock is used as the frequency and time base reference.
Options.1: An external 10-MHz clock is used as the frequency and time base reference. Provide a clean and stable 10 MHz reference to the appropriate back panel connector.

Options.0: Reference clock has been locked on.
Options.1: There was an error locking onto the reference clock signal. After an error the source is automatically switched back to internal reference clock.
Options.2: The device is busy trying to lock onto the reference clock signal.

Options.5: 72 MHz

/DEV8049/AWGS/0/SEQUENCER/STATUS.Description: Status of the sequencer on the instrument.

/DEV8049/AWGS/0/SEQUENCER/TRIGGERED.Description: When 1, indicates that the AWG Sequencer has been triggered.

/DEV8049/AWGS/0/WAVEFORM/INDEX.Description: Allows to select the index of the waveform in the waveform list for subsequent writing and reading.

/DEV8049/AWGS/0/WAVEFORM/MEMORYUSAGE.Description: Amount of the used waveform data relative to the device cache memory. The cache memory provides space for 32 kSa of waveform data. Memory Usage over 100% means that waveforms must be loaded from the main memory (128 MSa per channel) during playback, which can lead to delays.

/DEV8049/AWGS/0/WAVEFORM/PLAYING.Description: When 1, indicates if a waveform is being played currently.

/DEV8049/AWGS/0/ELF/LENGTH.Description: Length of the compiled ELF file.

/DEV8049/AWGS/0/ELF/CHECKSUM.Description: Checksum of the uploaded ELF file.

/DEV8049/AWGS/0/ELF/MEMORYUSAGE.Description: Size of the uploaded ELF file relative to the size of the main memory.

/DEV8049/AWGS/0/ELF/PROGRESS.Description: The percentage of the sequencer program already uploaded to the device.

/DEV8049/AWGS/0/DIO/STROBE/INDEX.Description: Selects the DIO index to be used as a trigger for the playback of a wave in connecton with waitDIOTrigger().

/DEV8049/AWGS/0/DIO/STROBE/SLOPE.Description: Select the signal edge that should activate the strobe trigger.

/DEV8049/AWGS/0/DIO/VALID/INDEX.Description: Index on the 32-bit of the DIO bus to be used as a VALID bit, i.e. a qualifier indicating that a valid codeword is available on the bus.

/DEV8049/AWGS/0/DIO/VALID/POLARITY.Description: Polarity of the VALID bit that indicates that a codeword is available on the bus.

Options.1: High: VALID bit must be logical high.
Options.2: Low: VALID bit must be logical zero.
Options.3: Both: VALID bit may be logical high or zero.

/DEV8049/AWGS/0/DIO/MASK/SHIFT.Description: Defines the amount of bit shifting to apply for the DIO wave selection.

/DEV8049/AWGS/0/DIO/MASK/VALUE.Description: Selects the DIO bits to be used for waveform selection in connection with playWaveDIO().

/DEV8049/AWGS/0/DIO/DELAY/INDEX.Description: Index of the bit on the DIO interface for which the delay should be changed.

/DEV8049/AWGS/0/DIO/DELAY/VALUE.Description: Corresponding delay value to apply to the given bit of the DIO interface in units of 150 MHz clock cycles. Valid values are 0 to 3.

/DEV8049/AWGS/0/DIO/VALUE.Description: Current value seen on the 32-bit DIO interface.

/DEV8049/AWGS/0/DIO/STATE.Description: When asserted, indicates that triggers are generated from the DIO interface to the AWG.

/DEV8049/AWGS/0/DIO/ERROR/TIMING.Description: A 32-bit value indicating which bits on the DIO interface may have timing errors. A timing error is defined as an event where either the VALID or any of the data bits on the DIO interface change value at the same time as the STROBE bit.

/DEV8049/AWGS/0/DIO/STROBE/WIDTH.Description: Specifies the expected width of active pulses on the STROBE bit.

/DEV8049/AWGS/0/DIO/VALID/WIDTH.Description: Expected width of an active pulse on the VALID bit.

/DEV8049/AWGS/0/DIO/ERROR/WIDTH.Description: Indicates a width (i.e. jitter) error on either the STROBE (bit 0 of the value) or VALID bit (bit 1 of the result). A width error indicates that there was jitter detected on the given bit, meaning that an active period was either shorter or longer than the configured expected width.

/DEV8049/AWGS/0/DIO/HIGHBITS.Description: 32-bit value indicating which bits on the 32-bit interface are detected as having a logic high value.

/DEV8049/AWGS/0/DIO/LOWBITS.Description: 32-bit value indicating which bits on the 32-bit interface are detected as having a logic low value.

/DEV8049/AWGS/0/OUTPUTS/0/AMPLITUDE.Description: Amplitude in units of full scale of the given AWG Output. The full scale corresponds to the Range voltage setting of the Signal Outputs.

/DEV8049/AWGS/0/OUTPUTS/0/MODULATION/MOD.Description: Select modulation mode between off, sine modulation, function generator modulation, and advanced.

Options.0: Modulation Off: AWG Output goes directly to Signal Output.
Options.1: Sine 1: AWG Output is multiplied with Sine Generator signal 0.
Options.2: Sine 2: AWG Output is multiplied with Sine Generator signal 1.
Options.3: FG 1: AWG Output is multiplied with Function Generator signal 0. Requires an installed Function Generator (FG) option.
Options.4: FG 2: AWG Output is multiplied with Function Generator signal 1. Requires an installed Function Generator (FG) option.
Options.5: Advanced: Output modulates corresponding sines from modulation carriers.

/DEV8049/AWGS/0/OUTPUTS/0/HOLD.Description: Keep the last sample (constant) on the output even after the waveform program finishes.

/DEV8049/AWGS/0/OUTPUTS/0/ENABLES/0.Description: Enables the driving of the given AWG output channel.

/DEV8049/AWGS/0/OUTPUTS/0/ENABLES/1.Description: Enables the driving of the given AWG output channel.

/DEV8049/AWGS/0/OUTPUTS/1/AMPLITUDE.Description: Amplitude in units of full scale of the given AWG Output. The full scale corresponds to the Range voltage setting of the Signal Outputs.

/DEV8049/AWGS/0/OUTPUTS/1/MODULATION/MOD.Description: Select modulation mode between off, sine modulation, function generator modulation, and advanced.

Options.0: Modulation Off: AWG Output goes directly to Signal Output.

/DEV8049/AWGS/3/DIO/DELAY/INDEX.Description: Index of the bit on the DIO interface for which the delay should be changed.

/DEV8049/AWGS/3/DIO/DELAY/VALUE.Description: Corresponding delay value to apply to the given bit of the DIO interface in units of 150 MHz clock cycles. Valid values are 0 to 3.

/DEV8049/AWGS/3/DIO/VALUE.Description: Current value seen on the 32-bit DIO interface.

/DEV8049/AWGS/3/DIO/STATE.Description: When asserted, indicates that triggers are generated from the DIO interface to the AWG.

/DEV8049/AWGS/3/DIO/ERROR/TIMING.Description: A 32-bit value indicating which bits on the DIO interface may have timing errors. A timing error is defined as an event where either the VALID or any of the data bits on the DIO interface change value at the same time as the STROBE bit.

/DEV8049/AWGS/3/DIO/STROBE/WIDTH.Description: Specifies the expected width of active pulses on the STROBE bit.

/DEV8049/AWGS/3/DIO/VALID/WIDTH.Description: Expected width of an active pulse on the VALID bit.

/DEV8049/AWGS/3/DIO/ERROR/WIDTH.Description: Indicates a width (i.e. jitter) error on either the STROBE (bit 0 of the value) or VALID bit (bit 1 of the result). A width error indicates that there was jitter detected on the given bit, meaning that an active period was either shorter or longer than the configured expected width.

/DEV8049/AWGS/3/DIO/HIGHBITS.Description: 32-bit value indicating which bits on the 32-bit interface are detected as having a logic high value.

/DEV8049/AWGS/3/DIO/LOWBITS.Description: 32-bit value indicating which bits on the 32-bit interface are detected as having a logic low value.

/DEV8049/AWGS/3/OUTPUTS/0/AMPLITUDE.Description: Amplitude in units of full scale of the given AWG Output. The full scale corresponds to the Range voltage setting of the Signal Outputs.

/DEV8049/AWGS/3/OUTPUTS/0/MODULATION/MOD.Description: Select modulation mode between off, sine modulation, function generator modulation, and advanced.

Options.0: Modulation Off: AWG Output goes directly to Signal Output.
Options.1: Sine 1: AWG Output is multiplied with Sine Generator signal 0.
Options.2: Sine 2: AWG Output is multiplied with Sine Generator signal 1.
Options.3: FG 1: AWG Output is multiplied with Function Generator signal 0. Requires an installed Function Generator (FG) option.
Options.4: FG 2: AWG Output is multiplied with Function Generator signal 1. Requires an installed Function Generator (FG) option.
Options.5: Advanced: Output modulates corresponding sines from modulation carriers.

/DEV8049/AWGS/3/OUTPUTS/0/HOLD.Description: Keep the last sample (constant) on the output even after the waveform program finishes.

/DEV8049/AWGS/3/OUTPUTS/0/ENABLES/0.Description: Enables the driving of the given AWG output channel.

/DEV8049/AWGS/3/OUTPUTS/0/ENABLES/1.Description: Enables the driving of the given AWG output channel.

/DEV8049/AWGS/3/OUTPUTS/1/AMPLITUDE.Description: Amplitude in units of full scale of the given AWG Output. The full scale corresponds to the Range voltage setting of the Signal Outputs.

/DEV8049/AWGS/3/OUTPUTS/1/MODULATION/MOD.Description: Select modulation mode between off, sine modulation, function generator modulation, and advanced.

Options.0: Modulation Off: AWG Output goes directly to Signal Output.
Options.1: Sine 1: AWG Output is multiplied with Sine Generator signal 0.
Options.2: Sine 2: AWG Output is multiplied with Sine Generator signal 1.
Options.3: FG 1: AWG Output is multiplied with Function Generator signal 0. Requires an installed Function Generator (FG) option.
Options.4: FG 2: AWG Output is multiplied with Function Generator signal 1. Requires an installed Function Generator (FG) option.
Options.5: Advanced: Output modulates corresponding sines from modulation carriers.

/DEV8049/AWGS/3/OUTPUTS/1/HOLD.Description: Keep the last sample (constant) on the output even after the waveform program finishes.

/DEV8049/AWGS/3/OUTPUTS/1/ENABLES/0.Description: Enables the driving of the given AWG output channel.

/DEV8049/AWGS/3/OUTPUTS/1/ENABLES/1.Description: Enables the driving of the given AWG output channel.

/DEV8049/AWGS/3/AUXTRIGGERS/0/CHANNEL.Description: Selects the digital trigger source signal.

Options.4: Trigger Out 1
Options.5: Trigger Out 2

/DEV8049/AWGS/3/AUXTRIGGERS/0/STATE.Description: State of the Auxiliary Trigger: No trigger detected/trigger detected.

/DEV8049/AWGS/3/AUXTRIGGERS/0/SLOPE.Description: Select the signal edge that should activate the trigger. The trigger will be level sensitive when the Level option is selected.

/DEV8049/AWGS/3/AUXTRIGGERS/1/CHANNEL.Description: Selects the digital trigger source signal.

/DEV8049/AWGS/3/AUXTRIGGERS/1/SLOPE.Description: Select the signal edge that should activate the trigger. The trigger will be level sensitive when the Level option is selected.

/DEV8049/AWGS/3/WAVEFORM/DESCRIPTORS.Description: Displays various properties of the current waveform: name, filename, function, channels, length, segment, hash.

/DEV8049/AWGS/3/WAVEFORM/DATA.Description: Allows to write (using vectorWrite) or read (using getAsEvent) the selected waveform data at the selected index.

/DEV8049/AWGS/3/SEQUENCER/PROGRAM.Description: Displays the source code of the current sequence program.

/DEV8049/AWGS/3/SEQUENCER/ASSEMBLY.Description: Displays the current sequence program in compiled form. Every line corresponds to one hardware instruction and requires one clock cycle (3.33 ns) for execution."

/DEV8049/CLOCKBASE.Description: Returns the internal clock frequency of the device.

/DEV8049/SYSTEM/OWNER.Description: Returns the current owner of the device (IP).

/DEV8049/SYSTEM/ACTIVEINTERFACE.Description: Currently active interface of the device.

/DEV8049/STATS/CMDSTREAM/BYTESRECEIVED.Description: Number of bytes received on the command stream from the device since session start.

/DEV8049/STATS/CMDSTREAM/BYTESSENT.Description: Number of bytes sent on the command stream from the device since session start.

/DEV8049/STATS/CMDSTREAM/PACKETSRECEIVED.Description: Number of packets received on the command stream from the device since session start.

/DEV8049/STATS/CMDSTREAM/PACKETSSENT.Description: Number of packets sent on the command stream to the device since session start.

/DEV8049/STATS/CMDSTREAM/PACKETSLOST.Description: Number of command packets lost since device start. Command packets contain device settings that are sent to and received from the device.

/DEV8049/STATS/CMDSTREAM/BANDWIDTH.Description: Command streaming bandwidth usage on the physical network connection between device and data server.

/DEV8049/STATS/CMDSTREAM/PROCESSING.Description: Number of buffers being processed for command packets. Small values indicate proper performance. For a TCP/IP interface, command packets are sent using the TCP protocol.

/DEV8049/STATS/CMDSTREAM/PENDING.Description: Number of buffers ready for receiving command packets from the device.

/DEV8049/STATS/DATASTREAM/BYTESRECEIVED.Description: Number of bytes received on the data stream from the device since session start.

/DEV8049/STATS/DATASTREAM/PACKETSRECEIVE.Description: Number of packets received on the data stream from the device since session start.

/DEV8049/STATS/DATASTREAM/PACKETSLOST.Description: Number of data packets lost since device start. Data packets contain measurement data.

/DEV8049/STATS/DATASTREAM/BANDWIDTH.Description: Data streaming bandwidth usage on the physical network connection between device and data server.

/DEV8049/STATS/DATASTREAM/PROCESSING.Description: Number of buffers being processed for data packets. Small values indicate proper performance. For a TCP/IP interface, data packets are sent using the UDP protocol.

/DEV8049/STATS/DATASTREAM/PENDING.Description: Number of buffers ready for receiving data packets from the device.

/DEV8049/STATUS/FLAGS/PACKETLOSSTCP.Description: Flag indicating if tcp packages have been lost.

/DEV8049/STATUS/FLAGS/PACKETLOSSUDP.Description: Flag indicating if udp packages have been lost.
